{"cursor":"2523","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn geometry, an 'interior angle' (or 'internal angle') is an angle formed by two\nsides of a polygon that share an endpoint. For a simple, convex or concave of\nthe polygon, this angle will be an angle on the 'inner side' of the polygon. A\npolygon has exactly one internal angle per vertex.\n\nIf every internal angle of a simple, closed polygon is less than 180Â°, the\npolygon is called convex.\n\nIn contrast, an 'exterior angle' (or 'external angle') is an angle formed by one\nside of a simple, closed polygon and a line extended from an adjacent side.\n\nâThe sum of the internal angle and the external angle on the same vertex is\n180Â°.\n\nâThe sum of all the internal angles of a simple, closed polygon is 180(n-2)Â°\nwhere n is the number of sides. The formula can by proved using mathematical\ninduction and starting with a triangle for which the angle sum is 180Â°, and then\nadding a vertex and two sides, etc.\n\nâThe sum of the external angles of any simple closed (convex or concave)\npolygon is 360Â°.\n\nThe concept of 'interior angle' can be extended in a consistent way to crossed\npolygons such as star polygons by using the concept of 'directed angles'. In\ngeneral, the interior angle sum in degrees of any closed polygon, including\ncrossed (self-intersecting) ones, is then given by 180(n-2k)Â° where n is the\nnumber of vertices and k = 0, 1, 2, 3 ... represents the number of total\nrevolutions of 360Â° one undergoes walking around the perimeter of the polygon.\nIn other words, 360kÂ° represents the sum of all the exterior angles. For\nexample, for ordinary convex and concave polygons k = 1, since the exterior\nangle sum = 360Â° and one undergoes only one full revolution walking around the\nperimeter.\n","linknr":97,"url":"Internal_and_external_angle","recorded":1374853902,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Internal_and_external_angle&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Internal_and_external